          "email": "rs8887@att.com",
          "username": "rs8887"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-08-13 08:24:03.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nThe comment says \"Say something nice\", but I find that difficult right now. Is it possible that Sonar is messing with you? :-)\n\nSeriously, it seems very undesirable to split classes into related pairs like this. The grouping of API methods and associated constants seems very natural, and this separation seems very kludgy.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "a88cdc23ed197f948f86f68e782cc21698463d2b",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-08-13 13:33:02.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\n> The comment says \"Say something nice\", but I find that difficult\n > right now. Is it possible that Sonar is messing with you? :-)\n > \n > Seriously, it seems very undesirable to split classes into related\n > pairs like this. The grouping of API methods and associated\n > constants seems very natural, and this separation seems very\n > kludgy.\n\nI kind of agree, though on the other hand, I don't like to see interfaces cluttered with things other than methods.  In any event, this seems to be more of a preference thing, so decided to just do it the way sonar demanded.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "713b31a234934ec531c039b8aea2f995aaebd31e",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 57,
          "name": "Pamela Dragosh",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pd1248@att.com",
          "username": "pdragosh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-08-13 15:41:57.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2\n\n> Patch Set 6:\n> \n> > The comment says \"Say something nice\", but I find that difficult\n>  > right now. Is it possible that Sonar is messing with you? :-)\n>  > \n>  > Seriously, it seems very undesirable to split classes into related\n>  > pairs like this. The grouping of API methods and associated\n>  > constants seems very natural, and this separation seems very\n>  > kludgy.\n> \n> I kind of agree, though on the other hand, I don't like to see interfaces cluttered with things other than methods.  In any event, this seems to be more of a preference thing, so decided to just do it the way sonar demanded.\n\nEasier to just satisfy the sonar versus personal preferences.\nAccording to Joshua Bloch, author of \"Effective Java\":\n\nThe constant interface pattern is a poor use of interfaces.\n\nThat a class uses some constants internally is an implementation detail.\n\nImplementing a constant interface causes this implementation detail to leak into the class's exported API. It is of no consequence to the users of a class that the class implements a constant interface. In fact, it may even confuse them. Worse, it represents a commitment: if in a future release the class is modified so that it no longer needs to use the constants, it still must implement the interface to ensure binary compatibility. If a nonfinal class implements a constant interface,\n\nall of its subclasses will have their namespaces polluted by the constants in the interface.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "c5a7c1537414c5b0f57f2a8a309416886b374ba5",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-08-13 16:57:49.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1\n\n(6 comments)\n\nUff large review, glad I didn't have to write it. Comments are mostly related to what I think are naming inconsistencies.\n\nI take it that you will do some testing with drools applications before it gets merged and I pulled it into the lab, right? as drools apps is not very good at catching issues introduced with these types of inspections, especially when service loaders, etc .. that are loaded dynamically.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
